  "prompt": "If you block someone on Instagram could they still see you in the followers list of an account that didn't block them and they already know?",
  "response": "No, if you block someone on Instagram, they will no longer be able to see you anywhere on the platform, including in the followers list of an account that didn't block them.\n\nHere's why:\n\n*   **Blocking removes all connection:** When you block someone, Instagram completely severs the connection between your accounts. This means they can't see your profile, your posts, your stories, or your presence in any follower or following lists.\n\n*   **Instagram's Privacy Design:** Instagram is designed to protect the privacy of users who choose to block others. Making blocked accounts visible in any list would defeat the purpose of blocking.\n\n*   **Their View:** From the blocked person's perspective, your profile will either disappear from their view entirely, or if they try to access it directly (e.g., using an old link), they won't be able to see your content and may see a message indicating that the page is unavailable.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Mutual Followers:** If you have a mutual follower, the blocked person might suspect that you are following that account, but they wouldn't be able to directly confirm it by looking at the follower list.\n*   **New Accounts:** The blocked person could create a new account and potentially see you in a follower list through that new account. However, this would be a violation of Instagram's terms of service if they are doing it to circumvent the block.\n*   **Third-Party Apps:** It's possible some third-party apps might, in theory, scrape and compile public data, but these are generally unreliable and could also be a violation of Instagram's terms.\n\nIn summary, blocking on Instagram is intended to completely hide your account from the blocked user. They will not be able to see you in the follower lists of other accounts, even if those accounts haven't blocked them.\n",
